BMS31004 Bioinformatics for Biomedical Science - Week 3

Module Coordinator Mark Dunning

Last modified: 24 Feb 2022

Module Overview

High-throughput sequencing is now established as a standard technique for many functional genomics studies; allowing the researcher to compare and contrast the transcriptomes of many individuals to obtain biological insight. A high-volume of data are generated from these experimental techniques and thus require robust and reproducible tools to be employed in the analysis.

In this module, you will be learning how to analyse RNA-seq count data, using R. This will include reading the data into R, quality control and performing differential expression analysis and gene set testing, with a focus on the well-respected DESEq2 analysis workflow. You will learn how to generate common plots for analysis and visualisation of gene expression data, such as boxplots and heatmaps.

Although we will use RNA-seq data as a case study, the format of the data and methodologies will be highly applicable to other types of high-throughput omics data.

Introduction

Measuring gene expression on a genome-wide scale has become common practice over the last two decades or so, with microarrays predominantly used pre-2008. With the advent of next generation sequencing technology in 2008, an increasing number of scientists use this technology to measure and understand changes in gene expression in often complex systems. As sequencing costs have decreased, using RNA-Seq to simultaneously measure the expression of tens of thousands of genes for multiple samples has never been easier. The cost of these experiments has now moved from generating the data to storing and analysing it.

There are many steps involved in analysing an RNA-Seq experiment.

Workflow image from Ting-you Wang’s RNA-seq data analysis page

Analysing an RNAseq experiment begins with sequencing reads. Traditionally, these are aligned to a reference genome, then the number of reads mapped to each gene can be counted. More modern approaches such as salmon quantify transcripts directly and do not require genome alignment to have taken place. Either approach results in a table of counts, which is what we perform statistical analyses on in R. While mapping and counting are important and necessary tasks, they are typically performed in languages other than R and so outside the scope of this course.

In these sessions will be starting from the count data and getting straight into the analysis. We will be following a workflow that uses the DESeq2 package.

Learning objectives

  • Configuring a new project in RStudio
  • Exploring and navigating a file system using R commands rather than the GUI
  • Importing RNA-seq counts via tximport and DESeq2
  • How the representation of data in DESeq2 differs from “tidy data”

Example dataset

The data for this tutorial comes from the paper, Induction of fibroblast senescence generates a non-fibrogenic myofibroblast phenotype that differentially impacts on cancer prognosis..

Cancer associated fibroblasts characterized by an myofibroblastic phenotype play a major role in the tumour microenvironment, being associated with poor prognosis. We found that this cell population is made in part by senescent fibroblasts in vivo. As senescent fibroblasts and myofibroblasts have been shown to share similar tumour promoting functions in vitro we compared the transcriptosomes of these two fibroblast types and performed RNA-seq of human foetal foreskin fibroblasts 2 (HFFF2) treated with 2ng/ml TGF-beta-1 to induce myofibroblast differentiation or 10Gy gamma irradiation to induce senescence. We isolated RNA 7 days upon this treatments changing the medium 3 days before the RNA extraction.

The sequencing reads for this experiment were uploaded to ArrayExpress Sequencing Read Archive (SRA) and processed using salmon. However, the workflow we will describe can be applied to other sources of count data.

We should check visually that the correct files are identified, but often we will need to obtain a list of file names, and their respective paths in R.

The list.files function from base R is a fundamental tool. As with all R functions, we can find out more using the help facility within RStudio

?list.files

From the description we can see that the default operation is to list all the files within the current directory. The output is an R vector; one of R’s most fundamental data types.

list.files()

This will print all the files in the directory. Sometimes we want files of a particular type (e.g. csv files that we can read into R). The pattern argument can be set to the name of a file extension that we are interested in.

## List all files in the current directory that end in .csv
## We will revisit the tx2gene file shortly

list.files(pattern=".csv")
[1] "tx2gene.csv"

The path argument can also be changed to list the contents of other directories

list.files(path = "meta_data/")
[1] "sampleInfo_corrected.txt" "sampleInfo.csv"

Importing the metadata

We refer to metadata as the data that describes the biological and technical characteristics of the samples we have sequenced. Examples of variables recorded in the metadata might include.

  • tumour / normal status
  • cell line
  • age
  • gender
  • date of collection
  • litter

We include the sample groups that we want to compare, and any potential confounding factors that we might need to address as part of our quality assessment. The metadata is stored in a spreadsheet and typically entered by-hand. When creating such data we should be mindful of some best-practice guidelines that will make our data easier to read into R.

See here for a round-up of common errors to be avoiding when creating spreadsheets Data Carpentry lesson on spreadsheet errors

The sampleInfo.csv in the meta_data folder contains basic information about the samples that we will need for the analysis. This includes the ID for the sample from SRA, an ID assigned by the researcher, and the cell type and developmental stage for each sample.

N.B. If the argument you want to change is the first argument listed in the help page you have to specify it’s name. R will automatically infer that you are supplying a value for the first argument (path in this case). Similarly, you don’t always need to specify the name of the second argument, and so on.

Hence, you might see the code written in this way. The / at the end of the path is also not required.

## a lazier way of listing the files in salmon_quant by not specifying the path argument.

list.files("salmon_quant")

Both code chunks produce the same ouput - and it is not very useful if want to identify the files that we can read into R. The issue is that the count outputs are divided into different directories (based on sample name), and R will only list the contents of salmon_quant itself. Hence we will need to add an extra argument recursive=TRUE to tell R to look into the different sub-directories for files.

quant_files <- list.files("salmon_quant/",recursive = TRUE)
quant_files
[1] "1_CTR_BC_2/quant.sf.gz"  "2_TGF_BC_4/quant.sf.gz" 
[3] "3_IR_BC_5/quant.sf.gz"   "4_CTR_BC_6/quant.sf.gz" 
[5] "5_TGF_BC_7/quant.sf.gz"  "6_IR_BC_12/quant.sf.gz" 
[7] "7_CTR_BC_13/quant.sf.gz" "8_TGF_BC_14/quant.sf.gz"
[9] "9_IR_BC_15/quant.sf.gz"

Although we don’t strictly need to for this example, it is a good idea to add a pattern argument to the list.files command. This will only list file names that contain a particular pattern. In reality the output of salmon typically includes more than just the quant.sf files we have distributed for this course.

quant_files <- list.files("salmon_quant/",
                          recursive = TRUE,
                          pattern="quant.sf.gz")

We have seen previously that functions such as read_csv and read_tsv can be used to read files into R. The read_tsv can be used in this case because the files are tab-delimited; even though they have unusual file extensions. The .sf file is particular to salmon, and the .gz means that the file is compressed. R is happy to read compressed files without any modification to the usual read_tsv code.

However, read_tsv is designed to read a single file at a time. To pick a particular file from the quant_files vector, we can use the [] notation in R. The number inside the [] is the index in the vector.

## Print the name of the first file
quant_files[1]
[1] "1_CTR_BC_2/quant.sf.gz"
## Print the name of the second file
quant_files[2]
[1] "2_TGF_BC_4/quant.sf.gz"

However, the read_tsv function doesn’t quite work as we expect.

The columns of interest here are Name and NumReads which are the transcript name and raw read counts respectively.

In theory, we could read each of these files and join them together using tools from dplyr (e.g. left_join). However, when it comes to reading files for Bioinformatics analyses there are usually packages available that will do the job far more efficiently than we could by-hand. The particular package we will using is called tximport. This package is often used as an intermediate step between salmon and DESeq2. In the case of salmon output, it performs a key pre-processing step.

Our differential expression analysis will be carried-out at the gene-level, so we need to perform an additional level of summarisation before we can proceed. Effectively we need to sum the counts for all exons that belong to each gene. The mappings from transcript to genes can be obtained by a pre-built database (such as Ensembl). We have provided such data in a csv file that we can read in (tx2gene.csv).

## Use col_names=FALSE, otherwise it will try and use the first row as headings
tx2gene <- read_csv("tx2gene.csv",col_names = FALSE)

We can import our dataset with the tximport package. The ignoreTxVersion argument needs to be set to TRUE; you might have noticed that the transcript names in the quant files have a version number at the end e.g. .1, so won’t match the transcript names in the tx2gene table.

library(tximport)
txi <- tximport(quant_files,type="salmon",tx2gene = tx2gene,ignoreTxVersion = TRUE)

Starting to explore the count data

We will be using the DESeq2 library to analyse this dataset. Along with the counts and metadata, a design for the experiment also needs to be specified. This will define how the differential expression analysis is carried out, but can be changed at a later stage so for now we will use Treated as our factor of interest.

Printing the contents of dds to the screen gives details of how the data are represented.

library(DESeq2)
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi, 
                                colData = sampleinfo,
                                design = ~Treated)
using counts and average transcript lengths from tximport

To confuse matters, the dds object is not accessed in the same way as the tximport output. However, the object is a lot more user-friendly. If we type the name of the object it will print in a convenient manner and not fill the screen with output.

On first inspection it might appear that the counts are stored in a data frame. If you ever need to check the data type of an object there a number of functions starting with the prefix is.. The data type is important as it will influence what functions can be used on the data. For instance, the tidyverse functions we have seen previously expect a data frame, and will not work on other data types

is.data.frame(counts(dds))
[1] FALSE
is.numeric(counts(dds))
[1] TRUE

So the object returned by counts is not a data frame. Therefore we cannot subset the data in the manner we are familiar with.

dplyr::select(counts(dds), `1_CTR_BC_2`)

However, all is not lost because DESeq2 includes some functions for accessing the data (as we will see later). The mechanism for accessing data from a count matrix is to use a pair of square brackets after the object name with the following convention [row_number,column_number]

cm <- counts(dds)
## the count for the first gene on the first sample
cm[1,1]
[1] 1579
## the count for the first gene on the second sample
cm[1,2]
[1] 1547

There are a few shortcuts if we want multiple rows (genes) and columns (samples)

cm[1,1:3]

The metadata columns can also be re-assigned. This useful in this case because we can see that condition is not stored as a factor, which could cause problems later-on when we want to use condition in the differential expression.

dds$condition <- as.factor(dds$condition)

Visualising library sizes

We can look at a few different plots to check that the data is good quality, and that the samples are behaving as we would expect. First, we can check how many reads we have for each sample in the DESeqDataSet. As we have seen, the counts themselves are accessed using the counts function; giving a matrix of counts. Going along the rows we will get the counts for a particular gene; and down each column are the counts for a given sample.

The sum of a particular column is therefore the total number of reads for that sample.

sum(counts(dds)[,1])
[1] 37966475

A convenience function colSums exists for calculating the sum of each column in a matrix, returning a vector as a result.

colSums(counts(dds))
 1_CTR_BC_2  2_TGF_BC_4   3_IR_BC_5  4_CTR_BC_6 
   37966475    42302522    33300044    39401926 
 5_TGF_BC_7  6_IR_BC_12 7_CTR_BC_13 8_TGF_BC_14 
   37716438    32599790    34273169    38522207 
 9_IR_BC_15 
   36478271

The overall number of reads obtained for each sample is important, as it will influence how we interpret the number of reads for a given gene. If the number of reads for a particular gene is doubled from one sample to another we cannot automatically assume that it’s expressed level is doubled. In a similar manner, if the number of reads for a given gene is 0 we cannot assume that the gene is not expressed.

Summary

  • Importing a set of files into R involves being able to define the path to these files
  • Specialised packages can be used to import data and store the data appropriately
  • RNA-seq counts are stored in the form of a numeric matrix - which is different to the usual tidyverse representation of data.
